---
import Layout from '../../layouts/Layout.astro';
---

<Layout title="Recruiting Philosophy | Family Portal" noindex={true}>
  <div class="min-h-screen bg-gray-100">
    <div id="loading" class="flex items-center justify-center min-h-screen">
      <div class="text-gray-500">Loading...</div>
    </div>

    <div id="content" class="hidden">
      <header class="bg-stars-navy text-white shadow-lg">
        <div class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-4 flex items-center justify-between flex-wrap gap-3">
          <div class="flex items-center gap-3 min-w-0">
            <a href="/family/" class="text-white/70 hover:text-white text-sm">← Family Portal</a>
          </div>
          <button id="logout-btn" class="px-3 py-2 bg-white/10 hover:bg-white/20 rounded-lg text-sm">Sign out</button>
        </div>
      </header>

      <article class="max-w-3xl mx-auto px-4 py-10">
        <header class="mb-10">
          <span class="inline-block px-3 py-1 bg-stars-gold/20 text-stars-navy text-xs font-bold uppercase tracking-wide rounded-full mb-3">Read this. Anchor on this.</span>
          <h1 class="text-4xl md:text-5xl font-bold text-gray-900 leading-tight">Stars Recruiting Philosophy</h1>
          <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mt-3">What we believe about recruiting — and what we expect from each other.</p>
        </header>

        <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-lg p-8 md:p-10 space-y-10 leading-relaxed">

          <section>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              Recruiting is loud. Rankings, NIL rumors, social-media highlight reels, parents in group chats trading hot takes about what coach said what.
              We're going to cut through it. This page is what we believe — drawn from veteran club directors, college coaches, and a decade of watching what actually works. Read it. Refer back to it. We will hold ourselves and each other to it.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stars-navy mb-3">1. Be the butter</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
              Here's the truth about June and July: college coaches don't show up to events to discover you. They arrive with a <strong>shopping list</strong> — names they already know, video they've already watched, schedules they've already memorized. They are not window shopping. They will not stumble across you.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              The work that gets you on that list happens <strong>now</strong>. In the spring. Weekly video. Direct emails to schools you actually want to play for. Camps. School research. <em>Be the butter.</em> The ingredient on every coach's list. That doesn't happen at Newberry — it happens in May.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stars-navy mb-3">2. Control the controllables</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
              Once a college coach is at your game, the athleticism question is settled. That's why she came. She's not deciding whether you can play. She's deciding whether you have the <strong>character</strong> to play for her.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">She's watching:</p>
            <ul class="space-y-1 text-gray-700 ml-6 list-disc">
              <li>How you handle a strikeout</li>
              <li>Your body language in the dugout</li>
              <li>Whether you pick up your teammates</li>
              <li>Whether you're the first one out and last one in</li>
              <li>Who picks up the gear</li>
              <li>Whether you make eye contact with your parents after every pitch</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mt-3">
              <strong>Coaches cross players off the list for things that have nothing to do with stats.</strong> The good news: every one of those things is in your control.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stars-navy mb-3">3. It's a game of failure</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
              A .300 hitter is a great hitter. That means failing seven out of ten times. There is no other arena in life where 30% gets you celebrated. Softball is built on failure.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              Recruiting decisions get made on the at-bats <strong>after</strong> the strikeout — not on the strikeout itself. Flush it. Pick up your teammate. Get back to work. Your best at-bat at a showcase might be the one right after you punched out, because that's the one she remembers.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stars-navy mb-3">4. You drive the bus. We navigate.</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
              You will hear other clubs say, "<em>The player drives the bus — we just play tournaments.</em>" That's how a lot of programs avoid responsibility. We don't.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
              <strong>You drive.</strong> You send the emails. You research the schools. You go to the camps. You post the video. You care more about your future than anyone else does, because it's your future.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
              <strong>We navigate.</strong> We track which coaches visit your profile. We run a CRM and push updates to coaches who are watching you. We have direct conversations with coaches we know — and we won't oversell you, because honesty is our currency. We help you build a school list that's wide enough to actually find your fit.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              The catch: this only works if you're in. <strong>If you're not driving, we can't navigate.</strong> We will match your effort. We will not replace it.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stars-navy mb-3">5. Honest evaluation</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
              There are 1,300+ college softball programs. Most families know the top 25. <strong>"D1 or bust" is dead.</strong> Cast a wide net — D1, D2, D3, NAIA, JUCO — and pick by <em>fit</em>, not prestige. The right school for you exists. It probably isn't the school your friend's cousin played for.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
              When we evaluate you, we're going to be honest. If we tell a coach you're coachable, you'd better be. If we tell her you compete, you'd better. Our reputation with college coaches is what makes our advocacy work — and we will not burn that on overselling anyone.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              That goes both ways. We'll be honest with you about where you fit. <em>Potential</em> means you haven't done it yet. Don't get drunk on rankings. Don't pick a school because they were the first to look at you. Have a real reason — coach, program style, location, major, level. Real reasons.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="bg-gray-50 rounded-lg p-6 -mx-2">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stars-navy mb-3">6. For parents — specifically</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
              College coaches are watching you too. They notice if your daughter looks at you for approval after every pitch. They notice if you're carrying her gear through the parking lot. They notice if you're the loudest voice in the bleachers.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
              We're not saying any of this to judge you. We're saying it because it's what coaches told us they look for. Decide what to do with it.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
              The best thing you can do is let her drive. Let her email coaches. Let her carry her gear. Let her struggle, and let her recover from the struggle without your face turning into the one she scans for relief. <strong>Coaches recruit independent kids.</strong> Help her become one.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-700">
              And when you have questions or concerns — bring them to the coaches directly, not to your daughter mid-game and not to other parents in a group text. We are here. We will be honest with you.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section>
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stars-navy mb-3">7. NIL, portal, rev-share — what's noise vs. real</h2>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mb-3">
              You're going to hear a lot about NIL deals, transfer portal moves, and revenue sharing. Almost all of it is noise for softball recruits.
            </p>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-6 list-disc">
              <li><strong>NIL:</strong> ~98% of softball programs have crumbs after football and basketball get the money. Real personal-brand NIL exists for a few players with massive social media reach. Don't pick a school chasing rumored money.</li>
              <li><strong>Transfer portal:</strong> It has tightened roster spots and changed how coaches recruit. The takeaway: your digital footprint — video, profile page, tracked emails — matters <em>more</em>, not less.</li>
              <li><strong>Rev-share:</strong> Same story. ~100 schools have meaningful money. The other 1,200 still need players who fit.</li>
            </ul>
            <p class="text-gray-700 mt-3">
              <strong>Pick the fit.</strong> Money is a side effect of being good and being recruited well. It is not a recruiting strategy.
            </p>
          </section>

          <section class="border-t border-gray-200 pt-8">
            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stars-navy mb-3">What we ask of you</h2>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-6 list-disc">
              <li>Send your video weekly. Even when you don't feel like it.</li>
              <li>Email coaches at schools you actually want to play for. Real reasons. Not blasts.</li>
              <li>Show up to camps.</li>
              <li>Play with confidence and respect for the game.</li>
              <li>Handle failure like a college player would — flush it, pick up your teammate.</li>
              <li>Be honest with us about how you're doing. We can only help if we know.</li>
            </ul>

            <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-stars-navy mb-3 mt-8">What we promise back</h2>
            <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-700 ml-6 list-disc">
              <li>We will track every coach we send your profile to.</li>
              <li>We will push updates to coaches when you have new film, new measurables, new milestones.</li>
              <li>We will be honest with college coaches about who you are.</li>
              <li>We will be the calm, steady voice when recruiting feels chaotic — because it will.</li>
              <li>We will help you find the right fit, not just the most prestigious offer.</li>
              <li>We will tell you the truth even when it's uncomfortable.</li>
            </ul>
          </section>

          <section class="border-t border-gray-200 pt-6 text-center">
            <p class="text-gray-600 italic">
              Coaches don't recruit players. <br class="md:hidden" />Players recruit colleges.<br />
              Our job is making sure they recruit you back.
            </p>
            <p class="text-gray-500 text-sm mt-6">
              Questions? Email <a href="mailto:mikeusry@gmail.com" class="text-stars-navy hover:underline">mikeusry@gmail.com</a>.
            </p>
          </section>
        </div>

        <div class="text-center mt-8">
          <a href="/family/" class="inline-block px-4 py-2 text-stars-navy hover:underline text-sm">← Back to family portal</a>
        </div>
      </article>
    </div>
  </div>

  <script is:inline>
    const AUTH_KEY = 'snw_family_auth';
    if (sessionStorage.getItem(AUTH_KEY) !== 'true') {
      window.location.replace('/family/login');
    } else {
      document.getElementById('loading').classList.add('hidden');
      document.getElementById('content').classList.remove('hidden');
    }
    document.getElementById('logout-btn').addEventListener('click', () => {
      sessionStorage.removeItem(AUTH_KEY);
      window.location.replace('/family/login');
    });
  </script>
</Layout>
